{"title_page": "Brendan Murray", "text_new": "{{For|the American music producer of the same name|Bighead (producer)}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Brendan Murray\n| background       = solo_singer\n| image            = Brendan Murray RedCarpet Kyiv 2017.jpg\n| caption          = Murray in 2017\n| birth_name       = Brendan John Francis Murray\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1996|11|16|df=yes}}<ref>{{cite news |last1=O'Loughlin |first1=Mikie |title=Irish X Factor star Brendan Murray is loved up with his student girlfriend |url=https://www.irishmirror.ie/showbiz/irish-showbiz/brendan-murray-x-factor-girlfriend-13605222 |accessdate=13 March 2019 |work=Irish Mirror |date=17 November 2018}}</ref>\n| birth_place      = [[Tuam]], [[Co. Galway]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]\n| origin           = \n| genre            = {{hlist|[[Pop music|Pop]]}}\n| occupation       = {{hlist|Singer}}\n| instrument       = {{hlist|Vocals}}\n| years_active     = 2014\u2013present\n| label = {{flat list|\n* [[Universal Music Group|Universal]] \n* [[Sony Music Entertainment UK|Sony UK]] \n}} \n| associated_acts  = {{hlist|[[Hometown (band)|Hometown]]}}\n| website          = \n| module           = \n}}\n\n'''Brendan Hugh Francis Murray''' (born 16 November 1996) is an Irish singer and former member of the Irish boyband [[Hometown (band)|Hometown]]. He represented [[Ireland in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017]] with the song \"[[Dying to Try]]\" but failed to qualify to the final. He then competed in [[The X Factor (UK TV series)|''The X Factor'']] UK in 2018, finishing in fifth place.\n\n==Life and career==\nBrendan was born in [[Tuam]], [[County Galway]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Brendan Murray through to X Factor semi-finals |url=https://www.rte.ie/entertainment/2018/1118/1011769-singer-brendan-murray-through-to-x-factor-semi-finals/ |accessdate=13 March 2019 |date=18 November 2018 |language=en}}</ref> He attended [[Presentation Primary School Tuam|St Patrick's Primary School]] and [[St Jarlath's College]], both in Tuam. \n\n===2014\u20132016: Hometown===\n{{Main|HomeTown (band)}}\nIn 2014, Murray became a member of the Irish boyband [[Hometown (band)|Hometown]], managed by [[Louis Walsh]]. The band achieved three chart successes in their home country, including the number one singles \"[[Where I Belong (HomeTown song)|Where I Belong]]\" in 2014, and \"[[Cry for Help (HomeTown song)|Cry for Help]]\" in 2015. Their debut album, ''[[HomeTown (HomeTown album)|HomeTown]]'', was released in November 2015 and peaked at number four in Ireland.<ref name=\"discography\">{{cite web|url=http://irish-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Hometown|title=Discography Hometown|publisher=Irish Charts Portal. Hung Medien (Steffen Hung)|last=Hung|first=Steffen}}</ref> In December 2016, the band announced that they'd be going on an indefinite hiatus.<ref>{{citeweb|url= http://www.hotpress.com/Hometown/news/Irish-band-HomeTown-split-to-pursue-individual-journeys/19190037.html?r15=1|title= Irish band HomeTown split to pursue individual journeys|date=8 December 2015|work=Hot Press|accessdate=13 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n===2016\u20132017: Eurovision Song Contest===\nOn 16 December 2016, Murray was announced as the Irish representative in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2017]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wiwibloggs.com/2016/12/16/ireland-brendan-murray-will-sing-eurovision-2017/160016/|title=Ireland: Brendan Murray will sing at Eurovision 2017|date=16 December 2016|publisher=Wiwibloggs|website=wiwibloggs.com|last=Gallagher|first=Robyn}}</ref>\nHis song, \"[[Dying to Try]]\", was released on 10 March 2017. He didn't reach the final, placing 13th out of the 18 contestants and requiring at least 10th to qualify.\n\n===2018: ''The X Factor''===\nIn 2018, Murray entered [[The X Factor (UK series 15)|Season 15]] of [[The X Factor (UK TV series)|''The X Factor'']] UK. During the Six Chair challenge he received a safe seat from [[One Direction]] singer [[Louis Tomlinson]], its first recipient, on the way to the live shows. He sang \"[[Break Free (song)|Break Free]]\" by [[Ariana Grande]] for his first ''X Factor'' live performance, with a 'This Is Me' theme. The second week, 'Guilty Pleasure' week, Murray sang \"[[Believe (Cher song)|Believe]]\" by [[Cher]]. On Sunday's results show, he was in the bottom three to compete in the sing-off. He was given equal votes by the judges, along with LMA Choir. The result went to deadlock, reverting to the earlier public votes. LMA Choir had the fewest votes and Brendan was saved and continued to the next week. On the third week of 'Fright Night', Murray performed \"[[Youngblood (5 Seconds of Summer song)|Youngblood]]\" by [[5 Seconds of Summer]]. During Week 4 he sang \"[[Everybody Hurts]]\" by [[R.E.M.]] for 'Movie Week'. He was eliminated in the semi-final on the Saturday show after he received the fewest votes from the public along with Danny Tetley, finishing in 5th place.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\" style=\"width:100%; margin:1em auto 1em auto; text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"4\" style=\"background:#BFBFBF;\"| ''The X Factor'' performances and results \n|-\n! style=\"text-align:centre;\"| Show\n! style=\"text-align:centre;\"| Song choice\n! style=\"text-align:centre;\"| Theme\n! style=\"text-align:centre;\"| Result\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Auditions\n| \"[[We Don't Have to Take Our Clothes Off]]\" \u2013 [[Ella Eyre]]\n| rowspan=\"4\" {{n/a}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Through to six-chair challenge\n|-\n| \"[[This Woman's Work]]\" \u2013 [[Kate Bush]]\n|-\n! Six-chair challenge\n| \"[[Everybody Hurts]]\" \u2013 [[R.E.M.]]\n| Through to judges' houses (Golden buzzer)\n|-\n! Judges' houses\n| \"[[Nothing Compares 2 U]]\" \u2013 [[Sin\u00e9ad O'Connor]]\n| Through to live shows\n|- \n! Live show 1\n| \"[[Break Free (song)|Break Free]]\" \u2013 [[Ariana Grande]]  ft. [[Zedd]]\n| This is Me\n| Safe\n|- style=\"background:lightblue;\"\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Live show 2\n| \"[[Believe (Cher song)|Believe]]\" \u2013 [[Cher]]\n| Guilty Pleasures\n| Bottom three (12th)\n|- \n| \"[[High and Dry]]\" \u2013 [[Radiohead]]\n| Sing-off\n| Safe (Deadlock)\n|- \n! Live show 3\n| \"[[Youngblood (5 Seconds of Summer song)|Youngblood]]\" \u2013 [[5 Seconds of Summer]]\n| Fright Night\n| Safe\n|- \n! Live show 4\n| \"[[Everybody Hurts]]\" \u2013 [[R.E.M.]]\n| Movie Night\n| Safe\n|- \n! Quarter-Final\n| \"[[Say Something (A Great Big World song)|Say Something]]\" \u2013 [[A Great Big World]] ft. [[Christina Aguilera]]\n| Big Band\n| Safe\n|- style=\"background:pink;\"\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Semi-Final\n| \"[[Run (Snow Patrol song)|Run]]\" \u2013 [[Snow Patrol]]\n| Get Me to the Final (Part I)\n| rowspan=\"2\"| Eliminated (5th place)\n|- style=\"background:pink;\"\n| \"[[I Have a Dream (song)|I Have a Dream]]\" \u2013 [[ABBA]]\n| Mamma Mia\n|}\n\n==Discography==\n===Singles===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:9em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:1em;\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\"| Album\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[Dying to Try]]\"\n| 2017\n| rowspan=\"2\" {{n/a|Non-album single|align=|style=|color=}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box\n| before = [[Nicky Byrne]]<br>with \"[[Sunlight (Nicky Byrne song)|Sunlight]]\"\n| title = [[Ireland in the Eurovision Song Contest]]\n| years = [[Eurovision Song Contest 2017|2017]]\n| after = [[Ryan O'Shaughnessy]]<br>with \"[[Together (Ryan O'Shaughnessy song)|Together]]\"\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Ireland in the Eurovision Song Contest |state=autocollapse}}\n{{Eurovision Song Contest 2017 |state=autocollapse}}\n{{The X Factor (UK)}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Murray, Brendan}}\n[[Category:1996 births]]\n[[Category:Eurovision Song Contest entrants of 2017]]\n[[Category:Irish Eurovision Song Contest entrants]]\n[[Category:Irish male singers]]\n[[Category:Irish mezzo-sopranos]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at St Jarlath's College]]\n[[Category:People from Tuam]]\n[[Category:The X Factor (British TV series) contestants]]\n[[Category:21st-century Irish singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male singers]]\n\n\n{{Ireland-singer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{For|the American music producer of the same name|Bighead (producer)}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Brendan Murray\n| background       = solo_singer\n| image            = Brendan Murray RedCarpet Kyiv 2017.jpg\n| caption          = Murray in 2017\n| birth_name       = Brendan John Francis Murray\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1996|11|16|df=yes}}<ref>{{cite news |last1=O'Loughlin |first1=Mikie |title=Irish X Factor star Brendan Murray is loved up with his student girlfriend |url=https://www.irishmirror.ie/showbiz/irish-showbiz/brendan-murray-x-factor-girlfriend-13605222 |accessdate=13 March 2019 |work=Irish Mirror |date=17 November 2018}}</ref>\n| birth_place      = [[Tuam]], [[Co. Galway]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]\n| origin           = \n| genre            = {{hlist|[[Pop music|Pop]]}}\n| occupation       = {{hlist|Singer}}\n| instrument       = {{hlist|Vocals}}\n| years_active     = 2014\u2013present\n| label = {{flat list|\n* [[Universal Music Group|Universal]] \n* [[Sony Music Entertainment UK|Sony UK]] \n}} \n| associated_acts  = {{hlist|[[Hometown (band)|Hometown]]}}\n| website          = \n| module           = \n}}\n\n'''Brendan Hugh Francis Murray''' (born 16 November 1996) is an Irish singer and former member of the Irish boyband [[Hometown (band)|Hometown]]. He represented [[Ireland in the Eurovision Song Contest 2017]] with the song \"[[Dying to Try]]\" but failed to qualify to the final. He then competed in [[The X Factor (UK TV series)|''The X Factor'']] UK in 2018, finishing in fifth place.\n\n==Life and career==\nBrendan was born in [[Tuam]], [[County Galway]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Brendan Murray through to X Factor semi-finals |url=https://www.rte.ie/entertainment/2018/1118/1011769-singer-brendan-murray-through-to-x-factor-semi-finals/ |accessdate=13 March 2019 |date=18 November 2018 |language=en}}</ref> He attended [[Presentation Primary School Tuam|St Patrick's Primary School]] and [[St Jarlath's College]], both in Tuam. Brendan recently went on tour (2019) to Manchester and 3 more cities. He did a meet and greet and sung songs, some of his own and some covers. - Macy Garth \n\n===2014\u20132016: Hometown===\n{{Main|HomeTown (band)}}\nIn 2014, Murray became a member of the Irish boyband [[Hometown (band)|Hometown]], managed by [[Louis Walsh]]. The band achieved three chart successes in their home country, including the number one singles \"[[Where I Belong (HomeTown song)|Where I Belong]]\" in 2014, and \"[[Cry for Help (HomeTown song)|Cry for Help]]\" in 2015. Their debut album, ''[[HomeTown (HomeTown album)|HomeTown]]'', was released in November 2015 and peaked at number four in Ireland.<ref name=\"discography\">{{cite web|url=http://irish-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Hometown|title=Discography Hometown|publisher=Irish Charts Portal. Hung Medien (Steffen Hung)|last=Hung|first=Steffen}}</ref> In December 2016, the band announced that they'd be going on an indefinite hiatus.<ref>{{citeweb|url= http://www.hotpress.com/Hometown/news/Irish-band-HomeTown-split-to-pursue-individual-journeys/19190037.html?r15=1|title= Irish band HomeTown split to pursue individual journeys|date=8 December 2015|work=Hot Press|accessdate=13 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n===2016\u20132017: Eurovision Song Contest===\nOn 16 December 2016, Murray was announced as the Irish representative in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2017]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wiwibloggs.com/2016/12/16/ireland-brendan-murray-will-sing-eurovision-2017/160016/|title=Ireland: Brendan Murray will sing at Eurovision 2017|date=16 December 2016|publisher=Wiwibloggs|website=wiwibloggs.com|last=Gallagher|first=Robyn}}</ref>\nHis song, \"[[Dying to Try]]\", was released on 10 March 2017. He didn't reach the final, placing 13th out of the 18 contestants and requiring at least 10th to qualify.\n\n===2018: ''The X Factor''===\nIn 2018, Murray entered [[The X Factor (UK series 15)|Season 15]] of [[The X Factor (UK TV series)|''The X Factor'']] UK. During the Six Chair challenge he received a safe seat from [[One Direction]] singer [[Louis Tomlinson]], its first recipient, on the way to the live shows. He sang \"[[Break Free (song)|Break Free]]\" by [[Ariana Grande]] for his first ''X Factor'' live performance, with a 'This Is Me' theme. The second week, 'Guilty Pleasure' week, Murray sang \"[[Believe (Cher song)|Believe]]\" by [[Cher]]. On Sunday's results show, he was in the bottom three to compete in the sing-off. He was given equal votes by the judges, along with LMA Choir. The result went to deadlock, reverting to the earlier public votes. LMA Choir had the fewest votes and Brendan was saved and continued to the next week. On the third week of 'Fright Night', Murray performed \"[[Youngblood (5 Seconds of Summer song)|Youngblood]]\" by [[5 Seconds of Summer]]. During Week 4 he sang \"[[Everybody Hurts]]\" by [[R.E.M.]] for 'Movie Week'. He was eliminated in the semi-final on the Saturday show after he received the fewest votes from the public along with Danny Tetley, finishing in 5th place.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\" style=\"width:100%; margin:1em auto 1em auto; text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"4\" style=\"background:#BFBFBF;\"| ''The X Factor'' performances and results \n|-\n! style=\"text-align:centre;\"| Show\n! style=\"text-align:centre;\"| Song choice\n! style=\"text-align:centre;\"| Theme\n! style=\"text-align:centre;\"| Result\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Auditions\n| \"[[We Don't Have to Take Our Clothes Off]]\" \u2013 [[Ella Eyre]]\n| rowspan=\"4\" {{n/a}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Through to six-chair challenge\n|-\n| \"[[This Woman's Work]]\" \u2013 [[Kate Bush]]\n|-\n! Six-chair cha