n annual pay for an industrial worker was 1,459 Reichsmark 1939, and for a privately employed  [[white-collar worker]] 2,772 Reichsmark.<ref name=\"Besoldung\">[http://www.lexikon-der-wehrmacht.de/Soldat/Besoldung.htm Die Besoldung eines Soldaten der Wehrmacht ] Retrieved 2017-12-26</ref>\n\n==References==\n===Notes===\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Cited literature===\n* ''Deutsches Reichsgesetzblatt Teil I, 1867-1945.'' [Cited as RGBl I]\n* {{cite book |last1=Hansen |first1=Michael |title=\"Idealisten\" und \"gescheiterte Existenzen\". Das F\u00fchrerkorps des Reichsarbeitsdienstes |date=2004 |publisher=University of Trier |url=https://ubt.opus.hbz-nrw.de/opus45-ubtr/frontdoor/deliver/index/docId/141/file/MichaelHansenDiss.pdf |language=German |trans-title=\"Idealists\" and \"failed existences\". The Leadership Corps of the Reich Labor Service |ref = harv}}\n\n{{Ranks, uniforms and insignia of Nazi Germany}}\n\n[[Category:Nazi paramilitary ranks]]\n", "name_user": "Wolfmann", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRank insignia 1943-1945:Three photos", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ranks_and_insignia_of_the_Reichsarbeitsdienst"}
{"title_page": "Hometown (band)", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{tone|date=January 2017}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name            = HomeTown\n| image           = File:Hometown (band) 2015.jpg\n| caption         = HomeTown in 2015. \n Clockwise from left: Dayl Cronin, Cian Morrin, Ryan McLoughlin, [[Brendan Murray]], Josh Gray and Dean Gibbons.\n| background      = group_or_band                                     \n| origin          = Ireland\n\n| years_active    = 2014\u20132016\n| genre           = Pop\n| label           = [[RCA Records]]\n| Current_members =\n* Dayl Croninn\n* Dean Gibbon\n* Josh Grey\n* [[Brendan Murray]]\n* Cian Morrin\n* Ryan MacLoughlin\n| Past_members    =\n* Gareth Borrow \n| website        =\n {{URL|wearehometown.com/}}\n}}\n'''HomeTown''' were a six-piece Irish [[boy band]], formed and managed by [[Louis Walsh]]. They were signed to [[RCA Records]], a division of [[Sony Music Entertainment UK]]. The six-piece vocal group were made up of singers from the four corners of Ireland. Walsh auditioned a thousand young hopefuls for his latest pop endeavour and spent over a ear whittling the numbers down until he finally settled on 5 members. Dean was the only member lucky enough to not have to endure the long audition process. HomeTown consisted of Cian Morrison, Dayl Croninn, Dean Gibbon, Josh Grey, Ryan MacLoughlin and [[Brendan Murray]].\n\nThe band had supported some well-known artists in the past two years. HomeTown opened for [[Olly Murs]] in Ireland in April 2015, supported [[The Vamps (British band)|The Vamps]] in Ireland and throughout the UK in 2016 and also supported [[McBusted]] in 2015.\n\n==Members==\n* Brendan Murray (born 16 November 1996, {{age|1996|11|16}} years old), Murray represented Ireland in [[Eurovision Song Contest 2017|the Eurovision]] in 2017 in [[Kiev]], [[Ukraine]], but failed to qualify for the grand final. He competed on the fifteenth series of The X Factor and was eliminated in the semifinals.\n* Dayl Cronin (born 8 December 1993, {{age|1993|12|8}} years old) Cronin started own dance school in longs yard, tower street, cork.\n* Dean Gibbons (born 17 February 1994, 24 years old) \n* Josh Gray (born 28 March 1997, {{age|1997|3|28}} years old)\n* Ryan McLoughlin (born 27 January 1994, {{age|1994|1|27}} years old) McLoughlin released single 'Nobody like You' on 25 August 2017.\n*Cian Morrin (born 2 October 1994, {{age|1994|10|02}}  years old)\n\n==Career==\n===Early Beginnings===\nThe band was originally composed of five members, Gareth Borrow ([[Derry]]), Ryan McLoughlin ([[Newbridge, County Kildare|Newbridge]]), Brendan Murray ([[Galway]]), Cian Morrin ([[Castlebar]]) and Dayl Cronin ([[Clonmel]]). They were picked out of a thousand applicants for a band project by Walsh.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.derryjournal.com/what-s-on/arts-culture/louis-walsh-picks-derry-s-gareth-for-new-boy-band-1-5958335|title=Louis Walsh picks Derry's Gareth for new boy band|work=derryjournal.com}}</ref> Borrow was later removed from the band and Walsh brought in two new members; Josh Gray ([[Blessington]]) and Dean Gibbons ([[Tallaght]]), turning HomeTown into a six piece band.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishmirror.ie/showbiz/irish-showbiz/hometown-louis-walsh-new-single-5371228|title=Hometown: Some people ask us for photos and then say we'll keep this for when you're famous|date=21 March 2015|accessdate=21 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n===2014\u201316: Debut album===\n{{Main|HomeTown (HomeTown album)}}\nTheir first single, \"[[Where I Belong (HomeTown song)|Where I Belong]]\", debuted at number one in Ireland, becoming the fastest-selling single from a debut act and the fastest-selling single from an Irish artist in 2014. The single was written by [[Kodaline]]. The band's second single, \"[[Cry for Help (HomeTown song)|Cry for Help]]\", was released on 27 March 2015 in Ireland. The song also reached number one on the [[Irish Singles Chart]]. The band began a signing tour around Ireland shortly after. They released their first single \"[[Where I Belong (HomeTown song)|Where I Belong]]\" in the UK on 24 July 2015, with an impact date of 4 September 2015.<ref>{{cite web|first=Pip|last=Ellwood|url=http://www.entertainment-focus.com/music-section/music-news/hometown-release-uk-version-of-where-i-belong-video/|title=HomeTown release UK version of Where I Belong video|publisher=Entertainment Focus|date=18 July 2015|accessdate=27 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/ten/news/2015/0402/691633-irish-boyband-hometown-hit-no-1-spot/|title=Irish boyband HomeTown hit No 1 spot|publisher=[[RT\u00c9 News]]|date=2 April 2015|accessdate=27 August 2015}}</ref> On 23 October 2015, Hometown released the third single \"[[The Night We Met (HomeTown song)|The Night We Met]]\" off of their debut album. It was written by [[Liam Payne]] of [[One Direction]] and Jamie Scott. On 20 November 2015, HomeTown released their [[HomeTown (HomeTown album)|self-titled debut album]], which debuted at number 4 on the [[Irish Albums Chart]]. In August 2016, the band released \"Roses\" as the fourth and final single from the album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.listenherereviews.com/hometown-release-new-song-roses/|title=HomeTown release new song \"Roses\"|publisher=Listen Here Reviews|date=8 August 2016|accessdate=16 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://celebmix.com/hometown-releases-new-single-roses/|title=HomeTown releases its new single \"Roses\"|publisher=CelebMix|date=August 2016|accessdate=16 December 2016}}</ref> In October 2016, the band had made their European debut in Madrid, Spain, where they played to a sold out Barclaycard Center at the festival Coca-Cola Music Experience alongside other acts such as [[Meghan Trainor]] and [[Bea Miller]]. In December 2016, Hometown announced that they would be taking a break from music to pursue individual projects.<ref>{{citeweb|url= http://www.hotpress.com/Hometown/news/Irish-band-HomeTown-split-to-pursue-individual-journeys/19190037.html|title= Irish band HomeTown split to pursue individual journeys|date=8 December 2016|work=Hot Press|accessdate=13 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 December 2016, [[Brendan Murray]] was announced as the Irish representative in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2017]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wiwibloggs.com/2016/12/16/ireland-brendan-murray-will-sing-eurovision-2017/160016/|title=Ireland: Brendan Murray will sing at Eurovision 2017|date=16 December 2016|website=wiwibloggs.com|publisher=Wiwibloggs|last=Gallagher|first=Robyn}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2017, Dayl Cronin took part in the Irish version of [[Dancing with the Stars (Irish TV series)|''Dancing With the Stars'']].\n\n==Discography==\n===Studio albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:10em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:16em;\"| Album details\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br>chart<br>positions\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Irish Albums Chart|IRE]]<br/><ref name=\"IRE\">{{cite web|url=http://irish-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=HomeTown|title=Discography HomeTown|publisher=Irish Charts Portal. Hung Medien (Steffen Hung)|last=Hung|first=Steffen}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[HomeTown (HomeTown album)|HomeTown]]''\n|\n* Released: 20 November 2015\n* Label: [[RCA Records]]\n* Format: CD, digital download\n| 4\n|-\n|}\n\n===Singles===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Title\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! Peak chart positions\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Album\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Irish Singles Chart|IRL]]<br/><ref name=\"IRE\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[Where I Belong (HomeTown song)|Where I Belong]]\"\n| 2014\n| 1\n| rowspan=\"4\"| ''HomeTown''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[Cry for Help (HomeTown song)|Cry for Help]]\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2015\n| 1\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[The Night We Met (HomeTown song)|The Night We Met]]\"\n| 59\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Roses\" \n| 2016\n| \u2014\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center; font-size:85%;\" colspan=\"22\" | \"\u2014\" denotes a single that did not chart or was not released.\n|-\n|}\n\n==Tour==\n===Headlining===\n* Sense Club, Cookstown \u2013 29 May 2015\n* Open Air Theatre, Scarborough \u2013 20 June 2015\n* Bents Park, South Shields \u2013 12 July 2015 \u2013 (2pm)\n* Westonbirt Arbertoreum, Tetbury \u2013 12 July 2015 \u2013 (8pm)\n* Delapre Park, London \u2013 17 July 2015\n* Edinburgh Castle, Edinburgh \u2013 18 July 2015\n* Feile Party in the Park (matinee), Belfast \u2013 2 August 2015\n* Greencastle Community Centre (evening), Donegal \u2013 2 August 2015\n* Culloville Community Centre, Newry \u2013 7 August 2015\n* Lytham Green, Lytham \u2013 8 August 2015\n* Vicar Street, Dublin \u2013 21 August 2015\n* Opera House, Cork \u2013 12 September 2015\n* UCH, Limerick \u2013 13 September 2015\n* Seapoint, Galway \u2013 26 September 2015\n* Great Northern, Bundoran \u2013 23 October 2015\n* Clanard Court, Kildare \u2013 25 October 2015\n* Headfort Arms, Kells \u2013 26 October 2015\n* Tullamore Court, County Offaly \u2013 27 October 2015\n* TLT Theatre, Louth \u2013 28 October 2015\n* Minella, Clonmel \u2013 31 October 2015\n* O'Connell Street, Dublin \u2013 29 November 2015\n* Vicar Street, Dublin \u2013 4 December 2015\n* Mount Errigal, Letterkenny \u2013 27 December 2015\n* Claremorris Town Hall, Claremorris \u2013 28 December 2015\n* Breffni Arms, Arvagh \u2013 29 December 2015\n* Clarnard Court, Kildare \u2013 1 January 2016\n* Radisson Athlone, Athlone \u2013 2 January 2016\n* INEC, Kerry \u2013 3 January 2016\n* Mcgettigans, Abu Dhabi, United Arab Emirates \u2013 17 March 2016 \u2013 (5pm)\n* Mcgettigans JLT, Dubai, United Arab Emirates \u2013 17 March 2016 \u2013 (9pm)\n* Jersey Opera House, Jersey Channel Islands \u2013 21 May 2016\n* Jacksons Hotel, Donegal \u2013 30 December 2016\u2013 Cancelled\n\n===Supporting===\n* [[Olly Murs]] \u2013 [[Never Been Better Tour]] (2015)\n* [[The Vamps (British band)|The Vamps]] \u2013 The Vamps UK Summer Tour (2015)\n* [[McBusted]] \u2013 [[McBusted's Most Excellent Adventure Tour|Most Excellent Adventure Tour]] (2015)\n* [[The Vamps (British band)|The Vamps]] \u2013 Wake Up UK Arena Tour (2016)\n\n=== Other gigs ===\n* Childline (2014)\n* Coca-Cola Music Experience (2016)\n* Beaulieu Convent School, Jersey Channel Islands (2016)\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://wearehometown.com/}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Irish boy bands]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2014]]\n[[Category:Musical groups disestablished in 2016]]\n[[Category:2014 establishments in Ireland]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{tone|date=January 2017}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name            = HomeTown\n| image           = File:Hometown (band) 2015.jpg\n| caption         = HomeTown in 2015. \n Clockwise from left: Dayl Cronin, Cian Morrin, Ryan McLoughlin, [[Brendan Murray]], Josh Gray and Dean Gibbons.\n| background      = group_or_band                                     \n| origin          = Ireland\n\n| years_active    = 2014\u20132016\n| genre           = Pop\n| label           = [[RCA Records]]\n| Current_members =\n* Dayl Croninn\n* Dean Gibbon\n* Josh Grey\n* [[Brendan Murray]]\n* Cian Morrin\n* Ryan MacLoughlin\n| Past_members    =\n* Gareth Borrow \n| website        =\n {{URL|wearehometown.com/}}\n}}\n'''HomeTown''' were a six-piece Irish [[boy band]], formed and managed by [[Louis Walsh]]. They were signed to [[RCA Records]], a division of [[Sony Music Entertainment UK]]. The six-piece vocal group were made up of singers from the four corners of Ireland. Walsh auditioned a thousand young hopefuls for his latest pop endeavour and spent over a ear whittling the numbers down until he finally settled on 5 members. Dean was the only member lucky enough to not have to endure the long audition process. HomeTown consisted of Cian Morrison, Dayl Croninn, Dean Gibbon Josh Grey, Ryan MacLoughlin and [[Brendan Murray]].\n\nThe band had supported some well-known artists in the past two years. HomeTown opened for [[Olly Murs]] in Ireland in April 2015, supported [[The Vamps (British band)|The Vamps]] in Ireland and throughout the UK in 2016 and also supported [[McBusted]] in 2015.\n\n==Members==\n* Brendan Murray (born 16 November 1996, {{age|1996|11|16}} years old), Murray represented Ireland in [[Eurovision Song Contest 2017|the Eurovision]] in 2017 in [[Kiev]], [[Ukraine]], but failed to qualify for the grand final. He competed on the fifteenth series of The X Factor and was eliminated in the semifinals.\n* Dayl Cronin (born 8 December 1993, {{age|1993|12|8}} years old) Cronin started own dance school in longs yard, tower street, cork.\n* Dean Gibbons (born 17 February 1994, 24 years old) \n* Josh Gray (born 28 March 1997, {{age|1997|3|28}} years old)\n* Ryan McLoughlin (born 27 January 1994, {{age|1994|1|27}} years old) McLoughlin released single 'Nobody like You' on 25 August 2017.\n*Cian Morrin (born 2 October 1994, {{age|1994|10|02}}  years old)\n\n==Career==\n===Early Beginnings===\nThe band was originally composed of five members, Gareth Borrow ([[Derry]]), Ryan McLoughlin ([[Newbridge, County Kildare|Newbridge]]), Brendan Murray ([[Galway]]), Cian Morrin ([[Castlebar]]) and Dayl Cronin ([[Clonmel]]). They were picked out of a thousand applicants for a band project by Walsh.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.derryjournal.com/what-s-on/arts-culture/louis-walsh-picks-derry-s-gareth-for-new-boy-band-1-5958335|title=Louis Walsh picks Derry's Gareth for new boy band|work=derryjournal.com}}</ref> Borrow was later removed from the band and Walsh brought in two new members; Josh Gray ([[Blessington]]) and Dean Gibbons ([[Tallaght]]), turning HomeTown into a six piece band.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishmirror.ie/showbiz/irish-showbiz/hometown-louis-walsh-new-single-5371228|title=Hometown: Some people ask us for photos and then say we'll keep this for when you're famous|date=21 March 2015|accessdate=21 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n===2014\u201316: Debut album===\n{{Main|HomeTown (HomeTown album)}}\nTheir first single, \"[[Where I Belong (HomeTown song)|Where I Belong]]\", debuted at number one in Ireland, becoming the fastest-selling single from a debut act and the fastest-selling single from an Irish artist in 2014. The single was written by [[Kodaline]]. The band's second single, \"[[Cry for Help (HomeTown song)|Cry for Help]]\", was released on 27 March 2015 in Ireland. The song also reached number one on the [[Irish Singles Chart]]. The band began a signing tour around Ireland shortly after. They released their first single \"[[Where I Belong (HomeTown song)|Where I Belong]]\" in the UK on 24 July 2015, with an impact date of 4 September 2015.<ref>{{cite web|first=Pip|last=Ellwood|url=http://www.entertainment-focus.com/music-section/music-news/hometown-release-uk-version-of-where-i-belong-video/|title=HomeTown release UK version of Where I Belong video|publisher=Entertainment Focus|date=18 July 2015|accessdate=27 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/ten/news/2015/0402/691633-irish-boyband-hometown-hit-no-1-spot/|title=Irish boyband HomeTown hit No 1 spot|publisher=[[RT\u00c9 News]]|date=2 April 2015|accessdate=27 August 2015}}</ref> On 23 October 2015, Hometown released the third single \"[[The Night We Met (HomeTown song)|The Night We Met]]\" off of their debut album. It was written by [[Liam Payne]] of [[One Direction]] and Jamie Scott. On 20 November 2015, HomeTown released their [[HomeTown (HomeTown album)|self-titled debut album]], which debuted at number 4 on the [[Irish Albums Chart]]. In August 2016, the band released \"Roses\" as the fourth and final single from the album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.listenherereviews.com/hometown-release-new-song-roses/|title=HomeTown release new song \"Roses\"|publisher=Listen Here Reviews|date=8 August 2016|accessdate=16 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://celebmix.com/hometown-releases-new-single-roses/|title=HomeTown releases its new single \"Roses\"|publisher=CelebMix|date=August 2016|accessdate=16 December 2016}}</ref> In October 2016, the band had made their European debut in Madrid, Spain, where they played to a sold out Barclaycard Center at the festival Coca-Cola Music Experience alongside other acts such as [[Meghan Trainor]] and [[Bea Miller]]. In December 2016, Hometown announced that they would be taking a break from music to pursue individual projects.<ref>{{citeweb|url= http://www.hotpress.com/Hometown/news/Irish-band-HomeTown-split-to-pursue-individual-journeys/19190037.html|title= Irish band HomeTown split to pursue individual journeys|date=8 December 2016|work=Hot Press|accessdate=13 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 December 2016, [[Brendan Murray]] was announced as the Irish representative in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2017]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wiwibloggs.com/2016/12/16/ireland-brendan-murray-will-sing-eurovision-2017/160016/|title=Ireland: Brendan Murray will sing at Eurovision 2017|date=16 December 2016|website=wiwibloggs.com|publisher=Wiwibloggs|last=Gallagher|first=Robyn}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2017, Dayl Cronin took part in the Irish version of [[Dancing with the Stars (Irish TV series)|''Dancing With the Stars'']].\n\n==Discography==\n===Studio albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:10em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:16em;\"| Album details\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br>chart<br>positions\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Irish Albums Chart|IRE]]<br/><ref name=\"IRE\">{{cite web|url=http://irish-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=HomeTown|title=Discography HomeTown|publisher=Irish Charts Portal. Hung Medien (Steffen Hung)|last=Hung|first=Steffen}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[HomeTown (HomeTown album)|HomeTown]]''\n|\n* Released: 20 November 2015\n* Label: [[RCA Records]]\n* Format: CD, digital download\n| 4\n|-\n|}\n\n===Singles===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Title\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! Peak chart positions\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Album\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Irish Singles Chart|IRL]]<br/><ref name=\"IRE\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[Where I Belong (HomeTown song)|Where I Belong]]\"\n| 2014\n| 1\n| rowspan=\"4\"| ''HomeTown''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[Cry for Help (HomeTown song)|Cry for Help]]\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2015\n| 1\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[The Night We Met (HomeTown song)|The Night We Met]]\"\n| 59\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Roses\" \n| 2016\n| \u2014\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center; font-size:85%;\" colspan=\"22\" | \"\u2014\" denotes a single that did not chart or was not released.\n|-\n|}\n\n==Tour==\n===Headlining===\n* Sense Club, Cookstown \u2013 29 May 2015\n* Open Air Theatre, Scarborough \u2013 20 June 2015\n* Bents Park, South Shields \u2013 12 July 2015 \u2013 (2pm)\n* Westonbirt Arbertoreum, Tetbury \u2013 12 July 2015 \u2013 (8pm)\n* Delapre Park, London \u2013 17 July 2015\n* Edinburgh Castle, Edinburgh \u2013 18 July 2015\n* Feile Party in the Park (matinee), Belfast \u2013 2 August 2015\n* Greencastle Community Centre (evening), Donegal \u2013 2 August 2015\n* Culloville Community Centre, Newry \u2013 7 August 2015\n* Lytham Green, Lytham \u2013 8 August 2015\n* Vicar Street, Dublin \u2013 21 August 2015\n* Opera House, Cork \u2013 12 September 2015\n* UCH, Limerick \u2013 13 September 2015\n* Seapoint, Galway \u2013 26 September 2015\n* Great Northern, Bundoran \u2013 23 October 2015\n* Clanard Court, Kildare \u2013 25 October 2015\n* Headfort Arms